Waze Project

Executive Summary

Background:

This anonymized public dataset is from Waze, a subsidiary company of Google that provides satellite navigation software. It has been made available for training machine learning and reporting techniques in an industry typical challenge of churn classification. However, this dataset contains irregularities, missing values, and outliers. The purpose is to find factors that drive user churn to provide recommendation strategies for Waze retention team. This includes fine-tuning a machine learning model using these factors to predict whether or not a Waze user will churn so that the factors most responsible for churn can form the basis of a retention strategy.

Findings:

Approximately 17.7% of users churned in the dataset, which might be too low to produce reliable analysis and model training. Correlation analysis showed that the number of days active,days driving and user tenure had been correlated towards a lower chance of churn (average -0.24). However, as active and driving had an extremely high (0.95) correlation with each other, only one was likely to be informative. In addition, some fields for percentages and ratios exceeded 100%, revealing errors in the dataset. This included `percent_sessions_in_last_month`, `percent_sessions_to_favorite`,`km_per_driving_day`,`sessions_per_day` ,`km_per_hour` and likely would be inreliable predictors of churn.

Higher number of days active (and driving days) was an indicator of engagement and therefore retention. The high sessions per day might indicate users that are experiencing technical issues and having to restart frequently as a result. High total navigations to a favorite spot as an indicator of churn makes sense in the context of experiencing issues with the application, as well as the app adding limited value to well-known routes. Beyond these indicators, the impact is less clear.

Modeling:

An XGBoost model provided the best analysis; however, the model's performance was much weaker than expected. Default decision-making threshold yielded a model with recall score of 0.215 and accuracy of 80.4% while an ROC-adjusted threshold (0.032) achieved higher recall (0.729) at the expense of accuracy (0.547).

Shap values were used to judge the impact of each factor within the data and make the recommendations below. The following recommendations should be taken with these scores in mind.

Model Results:

Active days within the last month were the strongest indicator ($-3.12<shap<2.73$), along with days after onboarding ($-2.61<shap<1.78$) and use of the favorites feature of navigation ($-1.16<shap<2.22$).

Recommendations:

  • activity_days: The first priority is users with less than 18 days of activity in the last month, which comprises 87.70% of all churn and only 59.47% of all users. Higher risk of churn was correlated to lower numbers of days, with 40.34% risk of churn at 3 days or less, down from 24.76% at 18 days or less.

  • total_navigations_fav1: Users with less than 28 navigations contain 30.76% of churn with only 33.79% of the population. Targeting this figure carries a lower risk but also a lower yield than activity_days.

  • n_days_after_onboarding: Within the first 365 days after onboarding is where churn is highest (14.87%), but this range is likely too wide to be actionable.

  • sessions_per_day: While there is a statistically significant difference for churned users ($p=4.77e-06$), there is too much noise and granularity of values to make a clear recommendation.

Conclusions

Even though the model's scores limit the usefulness of any analysis derived from them, the lower days of activity and favorite navigations form a base toward capturing between 16.14% to 25.26% of all churn. A low-risk low-cost strategy, such as a notification campaign, can be recommended from this.

Initial Pre-data Work

  1. What are you being asked to do?
  • Establishing whether a model and predict churn with the existing dataset
  • Identifying factors that drive churn based on model weights, feature importance
  1. What are the consequences of your model making errors?
  • False positives may leave to undue resource use
  • False negatives lead to churn
  1. Do the benefits of such a model outweigh the potential problems?
  • If the predictive ability is too low, the feature importances will not help inform the design of a retention campaign or allow for accurate user targeting.

Feature Engineering

Helper Function

In[4]:
def get_iqr(series):
    # calc IQR
    q_high= series.quantile(.75) 
    q_low =series.quantile(.25)
    iqr = q_high - q_low
    lower_lim = max(iqr - q_low *1.5,series.min())
    upper_lim = min(iqr + q_high *1.5,series.max())
    return lower_lim, upper_lim
In[5]:
def hist_outlier_plot(series):
    """
        Plots a histogram that shows IQR and median.
    """
    # get iqr limits
    lower_lim, upper_lim = get_iqr(series)
    # get set of outliers
    outliers = series[(series<lower_lim) | (series > upper_lim)]
    # plot
    sns.histplot(series,)
    bot,top=plt.ylim()
    for limits in [lower_lim,upper_lim]:
        plt.vlines(limits,bot,top,linestyles="dashed",alpha=0.5,colors="black")
    s_med= series.median()
    plt.vlines(s_med,bot,top,alpha=0.5,colors="black")
    plt.annotate(f"{outliers.shape[0]/series.shape[0]:.1%} Outliers ",(s_med*1.1,top*.95))
    plt.ylim(bot,top)
    plt.xlim(series.min()*0.95,series.quantile(0.95))
    plt.title(f"Outliers and Distribution")
    plt.show()

Use the get_test_scores() function to generate a table of scores from the predictions on the validation data.

In[31]:
def get_test_scores(model_name:str, preds, y_test_data):
    '''
    Generate a table of test scores.

    In:
        model_name (string): Your choice: how the model will be named in the output table
        preds: numpy array of test predictions
        y_test_data: numpy array of y_test data

    Out:
        table: a pandas df of precision, recall, f1, and accuracy scores for your model
    '''
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test_data, preds)
    precision = precision_score(y_test_data, preds)
    recall = recall_score(y_test_data, preds)
    f1 = f1_score(y_test_data, preds)

    table = pd.DataFrame({'model': [model_name],
                          'precision': [precision],
                          'recall': [recall],
                          'F1': [f1],
                          'accuracy': [accuracy]
                          })

    return table

# Generate array of values for confusion matrix
def plot_cm(model,x_test,y_test):
    """
        Generate a confusion matrix for a model.
    """
    y_hat_test = model.predict(x_test)
    cm=confusion_matrix(y_test,y_hat_test,normalize="all")
    sns.heatmap(cm,annot=cm,fmt=".1%",cmap=sns.color_palette("light:b",as_cmap=True),xticklabels=["Actual Retain","Actual Churn"],yticklabels=["Predicted Retain","Predicted Churn"])
    plt.yticks(rotation=0)
    plt.title("Prediction Results:")
    plt.show()
    # Plot confusion matrix

Explanation

The most impactful values being at the top of the feature impact chart, higher number of days active (and driving days) is a typical indicator of engagement and retention. It is possible that high sessions per day indicates users experiencing technical issues and having to restart frequently as a result. High total navigations to a favorite spot as an indicator of churn makes sense, as users are likely very familiar with their favorite routes and the app adding limited value to well-known routes. Beyond these indicators, the impact is less clear. In addition, most of the engineered features failed to add insight to the model, with some generating extreme outliers.

Any retention strategy should be aimed at users with high sessions per day and frequent navigations to favorite places.

Optimal decision threshold

The default decision is 0.5.

With imbalanced datasets, this threshold might not be ideal. Lets visualize the trade-off between precision and recall.

In[37]:
def get_clf_threshold(top_model,x_test,y_test,display):
    # Get probability predictions
    y_pred_proba = top_model.predict_proba(x_test)[:, 1]

    # Calculate ROC curve
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred_proba)

    # Find threshold that maximizes TPR - FPR
    optimal_idx = np.argmax(tpr - fpr)
    optimal_threshold = thresholds[optimal_idx]

    # Apply optimal threshold
    y_pred_optimal = (y_pred_proba >= optimal_threshold).astype(int)
    if display:
        # visualize ROC Curve
        sns.lineplot(x=fpr,y=tpr)
        sns.lineplot(x=[0,1],y=[0,1],linestyle="--", color="black",alpha=0.6)
        plt.xlabel("False Positive Rate")
        plt.ylabel("True Positive Rate")
        thresh_x = fpr[optimal_idx]
        thresh_y = tpr[optimal_idx]
        # annotate thresh
        plt.scatter(x=thresh_x,y=thresh_y,color="g",edgecolors="black")
        plt.annotate(f"{optimal_threshold:.4f}",(thresh_x+.005,thresh_y-.05))
        sns.despine()
        plt.title("ROC Curve with Threshold for Highest Recall")
        plt.savefig("roc.png", bbox_inches="tight")
        plt.show()
    return y_pred_optimal,optimal_threshold
In[38]:
y_pred_optimal,optimal_threshold = get_clf_threshold(top_model,x_test,y_test,display=True)

Post-Test Discussion:

Recall increased significantly at the cost of most other scores. Given the class imbalance of 17.7% and lack of data on the defining features of the app, it's hard to say if much improvement is possible.

There were a large number of anomalous values during feature engineering that can be clipped and/or dropped to try to improve results.

In[54]:
def pop_within_param(indicator,lower_thres,upper_thres,verbose=False,inside=True) -> float:
    """
    Returns a percent based on a column and its upper and lower limits.
    """
    total_pop = 0
    for df in [df_stay,df_churned]:
        if inside == True:
            ppop = df[(df[indicator] <= upper_thres) & (df[indicator] >= lower_thres)]["churned"].count()
        else: 
            ppop = df[(df[indicator] >= upper_thres) | (df[indicator] <= lower_thres)]["churned"].count()
        #per_pop = ppop/df.shape[0]
        #print(per_pop,",", ppop,"of",df.shape[0])
        total_pop += ppop
        total_sample = ppop
    if total_sample:
        tpop = total_sample/df_churned.shape[0]
    else:
        tpop = 0
    if verbose:
        print(f"based on {indicator}({lower_thres}-{upper_thres}):{tpop:.2%} of all churn ({total_sample} / {total_pop} {total_sample/total_pop:.2%})")
    return tpop,total_pop
In[55]:
def get_churn_range(col_name,max_window_size=10,pop_priority=True):
    top_val = 0
    top_pop = 0
    top_range=[]
    coeff = 0
    for j in range(1,max_window_size):
        width = j
        for i in np.arange(width,df[col_name].max(),width):
            result, sample_pop = pop_within_param(col_name,i-width,i+width)
            sample_coeff = result * sample_pop / df.shape[0]
            if pop_priority:
                if sample_coeff > coeff:
                    coeff = sample_coeff
                    top_val = result
                    top_range = [i-width,i+width]
                    top_pop = sample_pop / df.shape[0]
            else:
                if (result > top_val) & (sample_pop > top_pop):
                    top_val = result
                    top_range = [i-width,i+width]
                    top_pop = sample_pop / df.shape[0]
    print(f"Contains {top_val:.2%} all churn, within {top_range},{top_pop:.2%} of population")

Conclusion

The feature impacts do change with some mean-imputation applied and scores improve a little, but clearly the model isn't able to make use of most of the features it was given. Due to the number of issues with the data, it's likely that this particular dataset is too noisy and/or too small to make any big conclusions without getting either more application-related features in the set or more data to build the model through the noise. Session count and kilometer-related numbers would be worth reporting to the data engineering division to get more information on the what produces all of these outliers/heavily-skewed data.

Recall of 0.706 and accuracy of 0.605 are below industry standards, even after applying mean-imputation, but the recall score could be high enough to use if the retention strategy is a low cost one, such as sending reminders via notifications.

This model can only recommended under low-risk, low-cost circumstances.
